They having given the Devil this blood, as spoken before, they both fell again to their conjurations. First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched about Vandermast and threatened him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. Then began a great battle between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a good space. At last, Hector was slain, and the Trojans fled. Then a great tempest followed, with thundering and lightning, so that the two conjurers wished they had been away. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come for the Devil to be paid for the knowledge that he had given them.

ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 221 the matter the kingwas very glad hereof,and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg ment that I shaU appoint they all answered, that they were. Then were they bid to returne three days after. In that time Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground, and brought to the court the body hee did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards and Hkewise prepared three bowes and shafts for the three brethren all these kept hee secretly. The third day being come, came these three brethren, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bowes and shafts, saying, be not offended at what I have done, there is no other way but this to judge your cause See here is the body of your dead father, shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart, shad have aU the lands and goods. The two eldest prepared themselves, and shot at him, and stucke their arrowes in his breast. Then bid they the youngest to shoot but he refused it, saying, I will rather loose aU, then wound that body that I so loved living Had you ever had but halfe that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled, than to suffer his lifelesse corps thus to be used nay, you doe not onely suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame and speaking this, he wept.

In the evening Rush de maunded of his master what hee should doe the next morrow ? his master appointed him twice so much as hee did the day before, which Rush refused not, but got up earely in the morning, and went to the field, and about his worke so soone as his master was ready, he tooke his man's breakfast and came to the field, thinking to helpe Rush but he was no sooner come from his house but the Priest came to see his wife, and presently shee made ready some good meate for them to be merry withall, and whyle it was a dressing, they sate sporting together, who had beene there should have seene many loving touches. And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done aU that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvade then they sate dovroe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased ? I marvade that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home ? Ves, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I wdl goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and

Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice, probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? 

Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je

Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice, probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? 

Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je

ocr.sentence: Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous ?
ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 251 comme une exception parmi le commun des hommes, et que vous tiez ce qu'ils sont tous, perfides et trompeurs  l'occasion. Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

prediction.region: Ce qu'on peut voir dans une rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

prediction.region: Ce qu'on peut voir dans une rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? prediction.region: Ce qu'on peut voir dans une rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

prediction.region: Ce qu'on peut voir dans une rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis, la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice; probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon cur. Peut-tre, hlas! en interrogeant mieux ce cur, aurais-je

On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux, on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, on puise des motifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul, mais une force imprieuse et presque indpendante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

I have found, that my knowledge has beene. a heavy burden, and has kept downe my good thoughts but I will remove the cause, which are these bookes which I doe purpose here before you all to burne. They all intreated him to spare the bookes, because in them there were those things that after-ages might receive great benefit by. He would not hearken unto them, but threw them all into the fire, and in that flame burnt the greatest learning in the world. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it. They, not being content with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations, and raised up two spirits, one for each of them. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had, so that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. A great battle between the Greeks and Trojans then began, which continued for a good space. At last, Hector was slain and the Trojans fled. Then there followed a great tempest, with thunder and lightning, so that the two conjurers wished they had been away. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come for the Devil to be paid for the knowledge that he had.

And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

OF FRYER BACON. 243 George, who fought with the dragon and killed it. Vandermast, following his example, raised up Perseus, who also fought with his sea-monster and killed it, so both were released from their danger. They were not contented with this trial of their skill, and went further in their conjurations, raising up two spirits, one for each of them. 

Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had so that he might overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would, if only he would give him three drops of blood from his left arm. If he denied him that, then Vandermast would have power over him to do what he wished. The same demand was made of Vandermast by his Devil. To this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking they could overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both. 

Having given the Devil their blood, as spoken of before, they both fell again to their conjurations. First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched around Vandermast and threatened him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. Then a great battle began between the Greeks and Trojans, which lasted a good while. At last, Hector was slain and the Trojans fled. 

Following this, a great tempest with thunder and lightning began, making the two conjurers wish they had left. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come that the Devil would be paid for the knowledge he had given them.

And when Friar Rush saw that they were fighting together, he quickly blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of light therein whereby one might see the other. When he had so done, he took his truncheon in his hand and went into the choir among the thickest of the friars, who were fighting fiercely without light. He laid so lustily about that many of them he felled to the ground and left them there for dead. When he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as he went, he found standing in the portal of the choir, a great old desk. He immediately took the desk between both his hands and threw it over the portal into the choir among all the friars, hurting many sorely. Some had an arm broken, and others had a leg. Some had their noses cleanly pared from their faces, so that the blood ran in their mouths. Broken heads to the hard scalp were no dainty, for every man had one; there escaped none free away. Anyone who had been there would have had a goodly pastime to see the friars creep about the choir and, instead of "Domine labia," they cried out, "Alas!" and "Well away!

Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had so that he might overcome Vandermast. The same demand was made of Vandermast by his Devil. To this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking they could overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both.

prediction.sentence:
Another time, it happened that the Prior had to ride into the country for some business, and he called Rush, his servant, to him and said, "Rush, go to the courtyard and take with you a dish full of grease, and grease the wheels and axletrees of the wagon well. Make everything ready for tomorrow morning, as I must ride out early." 

Rush then departed his master and went about his business. Instead of grease, he took a large vessel full of tar and anointed the wagon all over with it, both inside and out, especially in the place where the Prior would sit. When he had finished, he returned to his master's chamber.

The Prior then asked Rush if he had done as he had commanded. "Yes, sir," said Rush, "you may ride whenever you please." And so, they went to their beds.

Over Fryer Bacon. 243 George, who fought with the dragon and killed it. Vandermast, following his example, raised up Perseus, who also fought with his sea-monster and killed it. So were they both released from their danger. They, being not contented with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations and raised up two spirits, one for each of them. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had so that he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would if he would give him three drops of blood from his left arm. But if he denied him that, Vandermast would have power over him to do what he wanted. The same demand was told to Vandermast's Devil. To this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking they would overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both.

Having given the Devil this blood, as is spoken of before, they both fell again to their conjurations. First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched around Vandermast and threatened him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. Then began a great battle between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a good while. At last, Hector was slain and the Trojans fled.

Then a great tempest followed, with thunder and lightning, so the two conjurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come that the Devil would be paid for the knowledge that he had.

Correct the text: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it. Vandermast, following his example, raised up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster and killed it, so they were both released from their danger. They, not being contented with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had, so that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would if he would give him but three drops of blood from his left arm, but if he did deny him that, then Vandermast would have power over him to do what he wanted. The same was told by Vandermast's Devil to him. To this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking they could overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both. 

Having given the Devil this blood, as is before spoken of, they both fell again to their conjurations. First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched about Vandermast and threatened him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. Then began a great battle between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a good space. At last, Hector was slain, and the Trojans fled. Then followed a great tempest with thundering and lightning, so that the two conjurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come that the Devil would be paid for the knowledge that he had given them.

Then, the Prior came into the choir and sat down in his place. As he looked around, he noticed that the Subprior was also present. With that, his heart began to remember the old anger that had fallen between the two of them, and he thought in his mind that he could never be avenged at a better time. Suddenly, he rose from his seat and approached the Subprior. With his fist, he gave him a good blow, and the Subprior, who was moved by the stroke, retaliated by hitting the Prior with his own blow. With that, they both fiercely attacked each other. Upon seeing this, the other friars rose from their seats, drew out their truncheons, and joined the fray.

And as they were all assembled together with one accord they chose a divell to goe and dwell among these religious men, for to maintaine them the longer in their ungracious living, which divell was put in rayment like an earthly crea-ture, and went to a religious house, and there he stood at the gate a certaine space all alone with an heavie countenance. Then within a while after the Priour came unto the gate and espied Rush the young man standing there all alone. Anon he said unto him, what dost thou here, and what wouldest thou have. The young man with great reverence answered and said Sir, I am a poore young man, and am out of service, and faine would have a maister. George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it, Vandermast followed his example and raised up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster and killed it, so both were released from their danger. They, not contented with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations and raised two spirits, one each. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had so that he might overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would, if only Bungye would give him three drops of blood from his left arm. If Bungye denied him that, then Vandermast would have power over him to do as he wished. Vandermast's Devil told him the same. To this demand from the spirits, both agreed, thinking they would overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both. Having given the Devil the blood as mentioned before, they both fell again to their conjurations.

First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched about Vandermast and threatened him. Then, Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. A great battle ensued between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a long time. At last, Hector was slain and the Trojans fled. Then a great tempest followed, with thunder and lightning, making the two conjurers wish they had been away. But their wishes were in vain, for now the time had come for the Devil to be paid for the knowledge that he had lent them.

George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it, Vandermast followed his example and raised up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster and killed it, so both were released from their danger. They, not contented with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations and raised two spirits, one each. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power he had so that he might overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would, if only Bungye would give him three drops of blood from his left arm. If Bungye denied him that, then Vandermast would have power over him to do as he wished. Vandermast's Devil told him the same. To this demand from the spirits, both agreed, thinking they would overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both. Having given the Devil the blood as mentioned before, they both fell again to their conjurations.

First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched about Vandermast and threatened him. Then, Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. A great battle ensued between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a long time. At last, Hector was slain and the Trojans fled. Then a great tempest followed, with thunder and lightning, making the two conjurers wish they had been away. But their wishes were in vain, for now the time had come for the Devil to be paid for the knowledge that he had lent them.
